<DOC id="APW_ENG_20101215.0720" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
Sasha Vujacic traded from Lakers to Nets
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
EAST RUTHERFORD, New Jersey 2010-12-15 19:18:11 UTC
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Slovenian shooting guard Sasha Vujacic transferred to the New Jersey Nets from the Los Angeles Lakers in a three-team NBA trade involving the Houston Rockets on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Nets sent veteran Joe Smith to Los Angeles, and swingman Terrence Williams to the Rockets, and, perhaps more important, earned two first-round draft picks.
</P>
<P>
"We're excited to get a player like Sasha who can come in and help us," Nets general manager Billy King said. "He's scrappy on defense and a good shooter on offense. He has experience with being on a champion. It's also an opportunity for us to get better with future draft picks."
</P>
<P>
The Nets acquired first-round picks from the Lakers in 2011, and the Rockets in 2012.
</P>
<P>
King said he expects 26-year-old Vujacic, who was not playing much with the Lakers, to come in and contribute right away, especially since starting shooting guard Anthony Morrow suffered a hamstring injury on Tuesday vs. Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
"He has to come in and learn the offense, but we're going to get him in and on the floor," King said of Vujacic, "because we need a player right now."
</P>
<P>
Vujacic, in his seventh year, averaged 4.8 points during his career in Los Angeles. He set the Lakers' single-season record for three-point accuracy in 2008, shooting at a .437 clip. He appeared in just 11 games this season, averaging 1.8 points.
</P>
<P>
Nets coach Avery Johnson will insert Vujacic into his regular rotation, quite possibly as early as Thursday when the Nets face the Los Angeles Clippers in Newark. Vujacic was set to arrive in New Jersey late Wednesday for a physical.
</P>
<P>
"We know he can shoot the ball," Johnson said. "It's nice to add someone with the capability to make a shot. We're excited to have him. We also acquired valuable picks, which gives us some flexibility. We need Sasha to play right away, because we need help at that position. I know he can come here and make shots."
</P>
<P>
Jordan Farmar, who played with Vujacic in Los Angeles, believes he can help.
</P>
<P>
"I describe him like a soccer player," Farmar said. "He has antics to get the crowd going. He also can shoot the ball well. He's feisty and competitive. He was sitting there and I know he's anxious to play. So, I'm happy for him. I'm looking forward to having him here. He's not going to come here and be a savior, but he brings experience and has a lot of big-game experience."
</P>
</TEXT>
