<HEADLINE>
Cyprus fully backs Bosnia ' s EU membership bid
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
NICOSIA, Cyprus 2010-12-29 10:54:47 UTC
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cyprus' foreign minister says the island nation fully supports the Bosnia-Herzegovina's bid for European Union membership.
</P>
<P>
Markos Kyprianou says Cyprus would like to see Bosnia become a member of the bloc as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Foreign Minister Sven Alkalaj says his country will seek Cypriot advice on its EU accession bid.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus joined the EU in 2004.
</P>
<P>
Alkalaj says the two countries also agreed to boost economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The two officials made the remarks on Wednesday after talks in the Cypriot capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="APW_ENG_20101217.0364" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
Vatican in new clash with China over church
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
VATICAN CITY 2010-12-17 11:47:02 UTC
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Vatican has sharply condemned a meeting of senior members of China's government-backed church, citing violations of religious freedom and human rights.
</P>
<P>
A Vatican statement Friday said the "unacceptable and hostile acts" have damaged the dialogue and "the climate of trust" between the Holy See and the Beijing government.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting last week, the government-backed church elected new leaders, including a prelate unrecognized by the Vatican to head its bishops' council.
</P>
<P>
Communist China forced its Roman Catholics to cut ties with the Vatican in 1951. Only state-backed churches are recognized, although millions of Chinese belong to unofficial congregations loyal to Rome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
